            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nProfessor Albright, in a seminar on post-colonial theory, paused. \"Sato,\" she said, looking right at him. \"A fascinating history there. Is your family from...\" He remembers the heat rising in his neck, the sudden, blank space in his mind. He mumbled something about his father being from California and changed the subject. The moment passed, but a small, sharp shame lodged itself within him. It was the first time his name felt like a question he couldn't answer, a history that belonged to someone else. (Occurred: Age 20)\n\n2.\nIt was a frigid Tribeca night in 2003. He was clutching a plastic cup of cheap prosecco, listening to a hedge-fund manager mispronounce \u2018Kiefer.\u2019 A wave of exhaustion, so total it felt physical, washed over him. He saw his future: a series of identical rooms filled with transactional chatter. The next day, he saw the job listing for the SF position. It felt less like an opportunity and more like an escape hatch, a path back to a city where the fog might actually clear his head. (Occurred: Age 32)\n\n3.\nHis first major SF show, 2006. He championed a young Mission district artist whose work was raw, messy, and political. The board was nervous. But on opening night, the room buzzed with an energy he'd never felt in New York. It was chaotic, earnest, and fiercely local. A young woman with paint-splattered jeans thanked him with tears in her eyes. That night, he wasn\u2019t just a curator from back East; he felt like he was finally part of San Francisco's defiant, complicated heart. (Occurred: Age 35)\n\n4.\nThe conversation that ended his marriage happened over a coffee table. \"It's a beautiful piece, Adam,\" his ex-wife had said, \"but it feels like a display. Like everything else.\" He looked around their apartment\u2014his apartment, really\u2014and saw it through her eyes. It wasn't a home, it was a gallery. The silence that followed wasn't angry, just deeply sad. He realized he had curated her right out of his life. The amicable split felt more like a quiet, mutual curatorial deaccession. (Occurred: Age 43)\n\n5.\nLast autumn, on the N-Judah. Rain slicked the windows as the train emerged from the tunnel at Duboce Park. A young couple, huddled together under one umbrella, laughed at something Adam couldn't hear. He felt a pang\u2014not of envy, but of profound loneliness, sharp and sudden. He looked down at his book, then back at the city unfolding outside. It was beautiful and heartbreakingly full of lives intersecting. He realized, with quiet clarity, that he was tired of just observing them from behind glass. (Occurred: Age 52)"
